<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41839376</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>26</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>26</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1096-0260</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>206</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>May</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Preventive medicine</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Prev Med</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Optimizing exercise prescription for blood pressure control after stroke or transient ischemic attack: A systematic review and meta-analysis.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>108550</StartPage><MedlinePgn>108550</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ypmed.2026.108550</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0091-7435(26)00056-3</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This study aimed to examine the dose-response relationships between different exercise modalities and blood pressure reduction in individuals after stroke or transient ischemic attack METHODS: Searches were performed in PubMed (1946), Web of Science (1975), Cochrane CENTRAL (1992), and EMBASE (1971) from inception up to December 10, 2025. Exercise dose was calculated as the product of duration, frequency, and intensity, expressed in metabolic equivalents of task minutes per week (METs-min/week).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">A total of 25 studies were included in the review. Aerobic exercise produced the greatest reductions in systolic blood pressure (SBP) at 590 METs-min/week (-3.79&#xa0;mmHg, 95% CrI: -5.95, -1.86) and diastolic blood pressure (DBP) at 520 METs-min/week (-1.91&#xa0;mmHg, 95% CrI: -3.56, -0.33). For combined aerobic and resistance training, the optimal doses were 780 METs-min/week for SBP (-7&#xa0;mmHg, 95% CrI: -10.05, -3.87) and 660 METs-min/week for DBP (-3.58&#xa0;mmHg, 95% CrI: -6.04, -1.23). Relative ranking analyses indicated that combined aerobic and resistance training at 780 METs-min/week and 660 METs-min/week produced the greatest reductions in SBP and DBP, respectively.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">These findings support evidence-based exercise prescriptions for blood pressure management in this high-risk population.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhang</LastName><ForeName>Yifan</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Graduate School of Physical Education, Myongji University, Yongin 17058, Republic of Korea. Electronic address: zhangyifan990825@163.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Huang</LastName><ForeName>Hao</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Jiangsu College of Nursing, No. 9, Science and Technology Avenue, Qingjiangpu District, Huai'an City, Jiangsu Province, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tan</LastName><ForeName>Zhiyuan</ForeName><Initials>Z</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Sport and Physical Education, University of Belgrade, Blagoja Parovi&#x107;a 156, 11000 Belgrade, Serbia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lei</LastName><ForeName>Lingzi</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Physical Education, Shangrao Normal University, 334001 Shangrao, Jiangxi Province, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Chen</LastName><ForeName>Xueying</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Graduate School of Physical Education, Myongji University, Yongin 17058, Republic of K